Weddings

Diane Nabatoff and Robert Machinist



Vows 
By                     
ABBY ELLIN

NOV. 11, 2007




Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story










Photo






NEW YORK, OCT. 27 No computer or phone in sight, the couple take their first dance. 

Credit
            Piotr Redlinski for The New York Times        



SEASONED daters will tell you that in-person chemistry is infinitely more significant than the virtual or pen-and-ink kind. After all, you can jibe with someone via e-mail messages, you can wax poetic (apologies to Shelley, Byron, Keats) over their text appeal, but none of that really counts until you meet face to face.No one knew this better than Diane Nabatoff, a film and TV producer in Los Angeles who has made movies with the likes of Antonio Banderas, Ray Liotta and Jason Patric. “The basic rule in dating is talk long enough to see if it is worth meeting,” she said, “but don’t invest any more than that.”But some rules end up on the cutting-room floor. And so it was that one August day in 2006 Ms. Nabatoff began an  e-courtship with Robert B. Machinist, 54, who runs  MB Investment Partners in New York, and races vintage cars.They met through Jean Goutal, an owner of Le Colonial restaurant in Manhattan who races   with Mr. Machinist and whose wife has been Ms. Nabatoff’s best friend since childhood.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

Ms. Nabatoff, 51, who said she had been engaged five times but never married, still hoped for the right guy. “You never know — you just sort of have to trust,” she said. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





Mr. Machinist, a father of four who had legally separated from his first wife more than a year earlier,  was “in the process of exploring what you do with the rest of your life,” he said. He had given up on the idea of meeting anyone.It sounded swell, but there was a hitch: they lived on different coasts.  So they resorted to texting, e-mail and nightly phone calls.Their exchanges  were “electric,” Mr. Machinist said. “She doesn’t descend into idiomatic blather. When you get to know someone from the sound of their voice, from their thought patterns and their speech cadence, it’s completely different from falling in love with their image and trying to fill in the blanks afterward.”Ms. Nabatoff was swept up by his voice, and their emotional conversations about “how we felt about our successes, our failures, who we were as people.” she recalled. “I could tell he really, really enjoys life.”
Photo






Jean Goutal, above, introduced them.

Credit
            Piotr Malecki for The New York Times        


As she prepared to leave  on a trip to Paris and London, they made a plan to meet in Manhattan that September. While overseas, Mr. Machinist was with her every step of the way — virtually, anyway. In their daily e-mail messages and phone conversations she would tell him where she was dining that night, and he would respond with rundowns of the best dishes and wines to order.As September and their first face-to-face meeting in New York approached, they  reverted to high school mode. “It was like, ‘Maybe we shouldn’t meet because I’m too scared we’ll lose this great new relationship,’” Ms. Nabatoff admitted. She asked for his photo; he sent one with his face hidden by his race helmet.Still not sure whether they would be pen pals or lovers, Ms. Nabatoff suggested that they go out two nights in a row, noting, “After spending so much time on the phone, I had to get used to being in his physical presence.”
Newsletter Sign Up
Continue reading the main story

  


