On the appointed night, he picked her up in Manhattan  in his  Porsche 911 GT3,  feeling  “like an awkward 15-year-old on a first date,” he said.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

The car, she said, was “too noisy, too uncomfortable and way too fast.” She calmed herself by  focusing on the voice she  knew so well.After their second date, he said he had to be in Los Angeles for a business meeting in 10 days. She  was his meeting, she later discovered.“He’s a smart and ambitious businessman but a soft, sweet and gentle human being,” Ms. Nabatoff said. “He’s hilariously funny, but the first person you would call for serious advice.”They began rendezvousing in Los Angeles, New York, Charleston, S.C., and Palm Beach, Fla. He sent flowers every time she returned home. On a trip to Napa, Calif., he proposed, and on Valentine’s Day this year, Mr. Machinist gave Ms. Nabatoff an antique locket featuring the racing picture with the hidden face.They were married on Oct. 27 before 100 friends and family at the New York Palace Hotel, in a room of candelabras and crystal chandeliers. The bride, in a Badgley Mischka beaded dress, was escorted down the aisle by Mr. Goutal, who said later, “I just thought they’d be great friends, and it turned into more.”Ms. Nabatoff’s patience was rewarded. “You just don’t know what’s around the corner,” she said.
Continue reading the main story






